I decided to take the next logical step and just play all three races as my main race. Eventually, I decided that I disliked ZvP sufficiently (as Zerg) to pick a certain race, and doing so also helps improve quicker. That said, having played random is relatively convenient for helping my teammates practice, as I can easily play whatever matchup they want to work on at a reasonably competent level.

I always valued mechanical precision back in Starcraft 1, and it’s an important part of SC2 for me too. fields.name: FactSet
fields.motto: We win games. That's a Fact.

fields.name: Against Malaria
fields.desc: Against Malaria works to help protect people from malaria.  Against Malaria funds anti-malaria nets, specifically long-lasting insecticidal nets (LLINs), and work with distribution partners to ensure they are used.   They also track and report malaria case data.

fields.name: Amnesty International
fields.desc: Amnesty International is a global movement of more than 3 million supporters, members and activists in more than 150 countries and territories who campaign to end grave abuses of human rights.

fields.name: Big Brothers Big Sisters
fields.desc: For more than 100 years, Big Brothers Big Sisters has operated under the belief that inherent in every child is the ability to succeed and thrive in life. As the nation’s largest donor and volunteer supported mentoring network, Big Brothers Big Sisters makes meaningful, monitored matches between adult volunteers (“Bigs”) and children (“Littles”), ages 6 through 18, in communities across the country.

fields.name: Boys and Girls Club of London, ON
fields.desc: The Boys & Girls Club of London is a non-profit recreational facility that provides activities for children whenever school is out. Our program services are planned to provide fun with a purpose. We offer recreation, social interaction and educational programs to build confidence, independence, self-esteem and self-respect for individuals and families in need. The Boys & Girls Club deals directly with the disadvantaged youth of our community. The Club gives children and teens of all abilities a place where they can learn and play away from the worries of the street.

fields.name: Brunau Foundation
fields.desc: The Brunau Foundation, founded in 1956 by the swiss « Integration Handicap » supports and efforts for social and professional integration of the handicapped. It offers 50 people yearly to absolve an education in an office environment.

fields.name: Bungie Foundation
fields.desc: We at Bungie are fortunate.  We have all had the unique opportunity to do something we love for the enjoyment of ourselves and for our fans.  Along the way, through partnerships with great charitable organizations and generous community efforts, we have also had the unique opportunity to give something back.  Now that we’re an independent company, we can do even more.  We created the Bungie Foundation with a clear goal: to reduce distress and suffering of children through entertainment.  This is no small endeavor, but together we believe we can make a difference.

fields.name: Camp Rising Sun
fields.desc: Camp Rising Sun is a camp for children who have faced a diagnosis of cancer. Camp gives children, aged 5-17, the opportunity to remember the joys of childhood; how to laugh, and how to play.

fields.name: Capital Area Food Bank of Texas
fields.desc: The Capital Area Food Bank of Texas (CAFB) provides food and grocery products to more than 300 Partner Agencies in 21 Central Texas counties. In Fiscal Year 2010-11, CAFB provided more than 24 million pounds of food. The CAFB service area covers 19,064 square miles in Central Texas. The mission of the Capital Area Food Bank is to nourish hungry people and lead the community in ending hunger. Food and grocery products provided by CAFB go to human and social service agencies. These Partner Agencies provide hot meals served on-site or groceries to Central Texans in need.

fields.name: Charity: Water
fields.desc: Charity: Water is a non-profit organization bringing clean, safe drinking water to people in developing nations. We use 100% of public donations to directly fund sustainable water solutions in areas of greatest need.

fields.name: Child's Play
fields.desc: Child's Play is dedicated to improving the lives of children in hospitals around the world through the kindness and generosity of the video game community and the power of play.

fields.name: Children's Hospital of Eastern Ontario (CHEO)
fields.desc: CHEO is a pediatric health and research center providing outstanding family-centered patient care, pioneering breakthrough research, and training the health care professionals of tomorrow.

fields.name: CIA Officers Memorial Foundation
fields.desc: The CIA Officers Memorial Foundation provides educational support to the spouses of CIA officers killed in the line of duty, and the children and spouses of officers who die on active duty as a result of accident, illness or other causes.

fields.name: College for Every Student
fields.desc:
The need for College For Every Student (CFES) is greater today than ever. 

As a nation, we face the challenge of educating our young people to become the skilled workers and leaders of tomorrow. For America to remain a land of opportunity and prosperity - and retain its role as a global economic leader - we must provide opportunities for all of our young people to realize their fullest potential. To do so, we must dramatically increase the college-going and graduation rates of low-income youth, who constitute the fastest-growing population in our public schools.

fields.name: Doctors Without Borders
fields.desc: Doctors Without Borders / Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF) is an international independent medical humanitarian organization that delivers emergency aid to people affected by armed conflict, epidemics, natural and man-made disasters, and exclusion from health care in more than 60 countries. A private, non-profit organization, Doctors Without Borders was founded in 1971 as the first non-governmental organization to both provide emergency medical assistance and bear witness publicly to the plight of people it assists.

fields.name: E.P.I.C.
fields.desc: E.P.I.C. (Everyday People Initiating Change) is a non-profit organization committed to bringing safe, clean drinking water to a number of villages in the developing world. Through the implementation of clean water wells, along with hygiene and sanitation education programs, E.P.I.C. provides a sustainable solution to a vast amount of the problems being faced by people in the developing world today.

fields.name: Exceptional Minds
fields.desc: A California nonprofit that offers training and employment opportunities for those on the autism spectrum who have a penchant for animation, design and video editing.

fields.name: First Hand Foundation
fields.desc: The First Hand Foundation is a not-for-profit, 501(c)(3) organization that provides funding so individual children may have access to health care that would otherwise be impossible. Our mission is to directly impact the health status of a young life. Since our inception in 1995, First Hand has distributed more than $17 million to impact 151,000 lives in 82 countries.

fields.name: Food for Lane County
fields.desc: Food for Lane County strives to eliminate hunger in Lane County, Oregon. Their goal is to create access to food for people in need. They believe that all people deserve access to wholesome, culturally appropriate, nutritious food, delivered with respect and compassion.

fields.name: Girls Who Code
fields.desc:
Launched in Spring 2012, Girls Who Code is a national nonprofit
organization working to close the gender gap in the technology and
engineering sectors. With backing from Twitter, Google, GE and eBay,
Girls Who Code programs work to educate, inspire, and equip high
school girls with the skills and resources to pursue opportunities in
engineering and technology.

Together with leading educators, engineers, and entrepreneurs, Girls
Who Code has developed a new model for computer science education,
pairing intensive instruction in robotics, web design, and mobile
development with high-touch mentorship led by the industry's top
female developers and entrepreneurs. In its inaugural program, Girls
Who Code is empowering 20 young women from NYC and will launch in
cities across the country in 2013.

fields.name: Goodie Two Shoes Foundation
fields.desc: The Goodie Two Shoes Foundation provides disadvantaged children and children in crisis with new shoes and socks as well as other items deemed essential for good health and positive development.

fields.name: Huntsman Cancer Foundation
fields.desc: Huntsman Cancer Foundation's sole purpose is to raise funds to support Huntsman Cancer Institute in their mission to understand cancer from its beginnings, to use that knowledge in the creation and improvement of cancer treatments, relieve the suffering of cancer patients, and provide education about cancer risk, prevention, and care.

fields.name: Make A Wish Foundation
fields.desc: Since 1980, the Make-A-Wish Foundation® has enriched the lives of children with life-threatening medical conditions through its wish-granting work. The Foundation\'s mission reflects the life-changing impact that a Make-A-Wish® experience has on children, families, referral sources, donors, sponsors and entire communities.

fields.name: Make A Wish Foundation - International
fields.desc: The Make A Wish Foundation - International grants the wishes of children with life-threatening medical conditions to enrich the human experience with hope, strength, and joy.

fields.name: MATHCOUNTS
fields.desc: In its 30th year, MATHCOUNTS is best known for its Competition Program that makes math as exciting as a school sport through a series of local and state competitions in all 50 states.  MATHCOUNTS also runs the Club Program that provides free resources and structure to any school that wants to have an organized math club, and recently launched the Reel Math Challenge, a free online contest that has students create their own math teaching videos.

fields.name: Meals on Wheels
fields.desc: The Meals On Wheels Association of America is the oldest and largest national organization composed of and representing local, community-based Senior Nutrition Programs in all 50 U.S. states, as well as the U.S. Territories.

fields.name: Room to Read
fields.desc:
Room to Read seeks to transform the lives of millions of 
children in developing countries by focusing on literacy and 
gender equality in education. Working in collaboration with 
local communities, partner organizations and governments, 
we develop literacy skills and a habit of reading among 
primary school children, and support girls to complete 
secondary school with the relevant life skills to succeed in 
school and beyond.

fields.name: San Diego Humane Society
fields.desc:
Serving San Diego County since 1880, the San Diego Humane Society and SPCA provides vital services to animals and people alike.

San Diego Humane Society and SPCA’s programs include:

    -sheltering and adopting animals
    -investigating animal cruelty and neglect
    -rescuing animals in emergency situations
    -positive reinforcement behavior training through public training classes
    -providing adult and youth education programs
    -sharing animals through pet-assisted therapy and more.

fields.name: Save the Children
fields.desc: When disaster strikes around the world, Save the Children is there to save lives with food, medical care and education and remains to help communities rebuild through long-term recovery programs. As quickly and as effectively as Save the Children responds to tsunamis and civil conflict, it works to resolve the ongoing struggles children face every day — poverty, hunger, illiteracy and disease — and replaces them with hope for the future.

fields.name: The Posse Foundation
fields.desc:
The Posse Foundation has three goals:

To expand the pool from which top colleges and universities can recruit outstanding young leaders from diverse backgrounds.
To help these institutions build more interactive campus environments so that they can be more welcoming for people from all backgrounds.
To ensure that Posse Scholars persist in their academic studies and graduate, so they can take on leadership positions in the workforce.

fields.name: The WD Foundation
fields.desc:
The Western Digital Charitable Foundation, “WD Foundation”, a California non-profit benefit corporation, was created in 1997 to support Western Digital’s philanthropic activities that support economic, social, educational, and health needs in our regional business communities within the United States. The Western Digital Foundation also supports global philanthropic programs through WD Foundations in Thailand and Malaysia.  

Currently the WD Foundation is donating money to the Red Cross relief effort to repair the damage done to Thailand in the recent floods.

fields.name: United Way of America
fields.desc: A national system of volunteers, contributors, and local charities helping people in their own communities.

fields.name: Vital Voices
fields.desc: Vital Voices Global Partnership is a leading non-governmental organization that identifies, invests in and brings visibility to extraordinary women around the world by unleashing their leadership potential to transform lives and accelerate peace and prosperity in their communities. Founded by U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton in 1997, the organization trains and mentors women leaders as agents of transformative change in economic development, human rights and political participation. The Vital Voices Global Leadership Network includes more than 12,000 leaders representing 144 countries who have trained and mentored 500,000 additional women and girls in their communities.

fields.name: Youth Service America
fields.desc: YSA (Youth Service America) improves communities worldwide by increasing the number and the diversity of young people, ages 5-25, serving in substantive roles. YSA coordinates Global Youth Service Day (www.GYSD.org) and Semester of Service, distributes over $1 million in grants annually, and provides resources and trainings.

fields.name: Zynga.org
fields.desc: Zynga.org is committed to helping to address real world challenges through social games. To date, Zynga players have generously donated more than $10 million to high-impact nonprofits meeting basic human needs around the world.

Game 1: Epic attempts to jungle invade.  Gives EY a triple kill that allows all lanes to snowball :(

Game 2: Epic's top swain against Naut looks promising until a dc, where swain gets set far behind.  All other lanes don't do well.  Epic takes dragons, but EY always gets kills in response.  Epic's win.
g6 didnt happen but i dunno how to delete it

Intel kinda just trolled around ^^;  Game 1 was intel playing Eve, Twitch, Heim, Yi Karma.

Game 2 was team Demacia, all commando skins.

Microsoft takes both easily.

Game 1 seems a slightly less normal lineup with Amazon's Rushwizard going mid as Ryze.  Google's Kennen has a couple good ults, but really no one can followup his stuns.

Game 2 shows everyone going back to their respective lanes on Amazon side.  Ends up being somewhat of a stomp for Amazon.

Amazon wins 2-0.

Game 1: Protect the Vayne came out from MS (Gragas, Janna, LeeSin, Yorick).  EY sent Plawg botlane as Viktor (w/ Soraka), Wukong mid, Udyr, and Olaf.  Vayne eventually got scary enough to destroy EY.

Game 2: team globals from EY (TF, Nocturne, Panth, Sona, Ashe).  Team AOE from MS (Wukong, Jarvan, Kennen, Galio, Maokai).  EY had a super fed Panth early game, but eventually MS was just able to small engage EY for a turn around fight that led to Baron.  Eventual push and continued AOE fight to win.

Game 2: Zeebz spawns Protoss, opens 4 gate into expo.  Cashed goes 3 gate robo until he sees expo, both go into mid game, zeebz has 2x the works, Zeebz rolls over cashed.

Game 4: Alski loses a lot of early lings to a spine crawler, Jade runs him down with 1 base roach.

Game 5: Zeebz spawns P again, 4 gates Karma and wins.

Game 1:

Amazon (home): blue
EY (away): last pick

Bans: twisted fate, morgana, kennen, trynd, shaco, morde

Amazon: Lee Sin, Shen, Soraka, Ryze, Graves
EY: Udyr, Janna, Rumble, Kog'Maw, Cassiopeia

EY pulled an early lead as Amazon kept entering team fights split.  However, Amazon managed to stall out an EY baron and turn around the next few team fights.  With all kills even, Amazon had the better team comp to push to win.

---

Game 2:

EY (home): blue
Amazon (away): first pick

Bans: TF, morgana, Cassiopeia, Trynd, Udyr, Ryze

Amazon: Lee sin, Tristana, Janna, Morde, Warwick
EY: Soraka, Corki, Nocturne, Kennen, Nautilus

Mordkaiser farm off the charts @.@  EY fell behind early and just unfortunately stayed behind :(

G1: ling/bling wars, qualcomm had an edge after a couple micro battles but got too greedy and died droning.
G2: zynga's joolz 3 gate rushes and wins with micro against qualcomm's defensive 3 gate
G3: qualcomm terran tries mech but lack of midgame pressure allows zerg to max on well-upgraded roach/infestor. zynga wins with mass roaches and mindcontrolled thors.
G4: qualcomm protoss opens FFE but lets 4 lings slip into his base. zynga zerg gets total scouting info for a very long time and overruns protoss with stephano-style mass roaches.
